Journalists in Awka, the Anambra State capital, who went to cover the ongoing proceedings of the Anambra State Election Petitions Tribunal were disappointed as the tribunal’s Secretary, Falilat Orire, told them she was under instruction not to release the names of judges of the tribunal to them. Orire said she was barred from releasing the names by the national headquarters of the Court of Appeal. On how the journalists can cover the proceedings without the names of judges, she said, “Write a letter to my bosses for the names to be made available to you, and if the request is granted, I will release their names.” Meanwhile, the panel of three of judges during preliminary hearing on consolidation of petition by Chris Uba said only the Court of Appeal could decide the fate of the petition. Sen. Andy Uba of the APC and his younger brother, Chris Uba of PDP had filed a suit against Dr. Ifeanyi Ubah, the winner of the Anambra South Senatorial District election. The two brothers had approached the tribunal challenging the victory of Ifeanyi Ubah of the Young Democratic Party (YPP) asking that his victory be set aside.  As Andy Uba hit the cul-de-sac Court of Appeal President and 2019 electoral disputes The Sokoto debacle and the Supreme Court Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin